## Findings in `app.js`

### 1. No authentication/authorization on `/users` (Medium-High)
Lines 11–16 expose user data (including emails) to any unauthenticated caller. Even if the data is seeded/mock, this pattern risks being shipped as-is. Add auth middleware (e.g., `passport`, JWT verification) before the route.

### 2. Missing security headers (Medium)
No `helmet()` is registered. Add:
```js
const helmet = require('helmet');
app.use(helmet());
```
This sets `X-Content-Type-Options`, `Strict-Transport-Security`, `X-Frame-Options`, CSP, etc.

### 3. No rate limiting (Medium)
Both endpoints are unauthenticated and unthrottled — trivial to abuse for DoS or scraping. Add `express-rate-limit`.

### 4. No CORS policy (Low-Medium)
Express defaults to no `Access-Control-Allow-Origin`, which is safer than `*`, but if a browser frontend is added later, an overly permissive CORS config is a common mistake. Configure `cors({ origin: <allowlist> })` explicitly.

### 5. No global error handler (Low)
An unhandled error in a route would propagate Express's default handler, which in development leaks stack traces. Add a 4-arg error middleware and ensure `NODE_ENV=production` in prod.

### 6. No body size / parser hardening (Low)
No body parser is currently attached, but if `express.json()` gets added later, set a `limit` (e.g., `'100kb'`) to resist payload-based DoS.

### 7. HTTP-only listener (Low, environment-dependent)
`app.listen(3000, ...)` serves plaintext. Terminate TLS at a reverse proxy (nginx, ALB) or use `https.createServer`.

### 8. No request logging / audit trail (Low)
Add `morgan` or structured logging so incident response has data to work with.

